Imagine a world in which amputees can not only operate a prosthetic limb, but actually feel them as if they were a part of your body. You already live here.

Researches at the Applied Physics Laboratory at John Hopkins university have created and successfully tested a prosthetic hand which wires directly into the brain, allowing its user to actually feel a sense of touch.

The hand operates by connecting to the brain‚Äôs sensory and motor cortexes through electrodes, which then feed back to the hand. Researches conducted a test in which they would apply pressure to one of the 5 fingers. According to Darpa, the volunteer was able to determine each individual finger with nearly 100% accuracy.
